Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Bring a #large saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} to the boil.

Peel and slice the @potatoes{450} into 1cm thick rounds. Once boiling, add the potato slices to the water and simmer until just tender, ~{8-12%minutes}.

> TIP: The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through them.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a garlic press). Trim the @green beans{150}.

Once the potatoes are cooked, reserve some of the potato cooking water (@reserved potato water{75}ml), then carefully drain in a #colander{}. Set the pan aside.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #medium frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add the shallot and cook until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add the @creme fraiche{150}g, @vegetable stock paste{10} and reserved potato water. Mix together, bring to the boil, then remove from the heat. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Lay the cooked potato slices in layers in an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}, then pour over the creamy sauce.

Pop the @British honey mustard sausages{4} onto a #baking tray{}. When the oven is hot, roast on the middle shelf until golden brown and cooked through, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

> The sausages are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

After ~{5%minutes}, add the gratin to the top shelf and bake until golden and bubbly, ~{15-20%minutes}.

> TIP: Put the dish onto a baking tray to catch any drips.

While everything bakes, fill the (now empty) #potato saucepan{} with water and put back on to boil. Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}.

Clean out the #frying pan{} and pop on medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Once hot, add the onion and cook, stirring frequently, until soft and sweet, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Add the @balsamic vinegar{12} and cook until evaporated and sticky, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir the @water for the gravy{200%ml} into the onions and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @red wine stock paste{28}, then lower the heat and simmer until your gravy has reduced and thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Add a splash of water if it gets too thick.

> TIP: Add a knob of butter (if you have any) for extra flavour.

When the sausages and gratin have ~{5%minutes} of cooking time remaining, add the green beans to the pan of boiling water with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Cook until just tender, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Drain the beans in a colander, then return to the #saucepan{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss in @?olive oil{} if you'd like.

When everything is ready, serve the sausages, gratin and beans on your plates. Spoon over the red onion gravy to finish.

Enjoy!